This is a Ceasar shift cipher.

==============================================================
SOLUTION
==============================================================

Cipher type : Caesar shift (ROT-N), single key over the 26-letter
              uppercase Latin alphabet.

Method
------
1. Brute force all 26 possible shift values.
2. Score each candidate plaintext by counting how many whitespace-
   delimited tokens appear in the Latin vocabulary list
   (../misc/latin_words.txt, ~28 k entries).
3. Shift 7 scores 6 Latin word matches; every other shift scores 0.
4. The codeword is extracted from the disclosure phrase embedded in
   the plaintext: "DICTUM ARCANUM EST <CODEWORD>" (Latin: "The secret
   motto is <CODEWORD>").

Ciphertext
----------
MHILY LZA ZBHL XBPZXBL MVYABUHL HWWPBZ JSHBKPBZ JHLJBZ
KPJABT HYJHUBT LZA ULBAYVU

Plaintext (shift = 7)
---------------------
FABER EST SUAE QUISQUE FORTUNAE APPIUS CLAUDIUS CAECUS
DICTUM ARCANUM EST NEUTRON

Once I saw the candidate plaintext, I identified the language as
Latin.  I grabbed a latin word list, and then added dictionary
checking.  Therefore, this solution took two passes.  If one
wanted to do it in one pass, one could do a web search for the
text and look for a match.  I chose a half-way approach -- knowing
the language but not directly searching for the text.

Translation
-----------
Line 1: "Faber est suae quisque fortunae, Appius Claudius Caecus"
        ("Every man is the artisan of his own fortune" — a maxim
        attributed to the Roman censor Appius Claudius Caecus, c. 312 BC)

Line 2: "Dictum arcanum est NEUTRON"
        ("The secret motto is NEUTRON")

Codeword : NEUTRON

Script : decrypt_stage02.py
